  <h1>Dietary Information</h1>
  <p>This page provides information about different dietary requirements and lifestyles.</p>

  <h2>Common Dietary Requirements</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Vegan:</strong> A diet that excludes all animal products, including meat, dairy, eggs, and honey.</li>
    <li><strong>Vegetarian:</strong> Excludes meat but may include dairy and eggs. Variations include lacto-vegetarian, ovo-vegetarian, and lacto-ovo-vegetarian.</li>
    <li><strong>Pescatarian:</strong> Includes fish and seafood in addition to plant-based foods but excludes other meats.</li>
    <li><strong>Gluten-Free:</strong> Eliminates foods that contain gluten, a protein found in wheat, barley, and rye.</li>
    <li><strong>Lactose-Free:</strong> Excludes lactose, the sugar found in milk and dairy products. Suitable for those with lactose intolerance.</li>
    <li><strong>Low-Carb:</strong> Focuses on reducing carbohydrate intake, often used for weight management and blood sugar control.</li>
    <li><strong>High-Protein:</strong> Emphasizes protein-rich foods and may be used for muscle building and weight loss.</li>
    <li><strong>Raw Vegan:</strong> A vegan diet that consists of uncooked, unprocessed plant-based foods.</li>
    <li><strong>Keto:</strong> A high-fat, low-carb diet that encourages ketosis, a metabolic state where the body burns fat for energy.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Benefits and Considerations</h2>
  <p>Each dietary requirement has its own benefits and considerations. It's important to choose a diet that aligns with your health goals and lifestyle preferences.</p>
